bio:
Hey there,

I have the greatest job in the world, which is working in a lab with many 3D printers! Many of them are delta printers. Thats where i started, because they just look amazing while printing. We also have a couple of cartesian machines, like the Prusa i3 (regular old chinese model) and a core-xy type machine.

I started off with graduating in Game Art, which really helps a lot with modelling 3D objects. Many times, it has saved me for all specific needs around printers, or at home. As most problems are unique, I can manipulate everything to my wish quite well.

A 3D printing substitute teacher. I dropped out of a PhD program in 2013 and considered getting a license to teach science full time. But then I thought of a way to get back into teaching that requires less money than getting my license. Now I run a start up 3D printing education business called www.tomorrowseinsteins.com. I am a licensed short term substitute teacher available through Teachers on Call to teach subjects including the basics of 3D printing, modeling and scanning to your students for up to a two weeks. I think this is ideal for geometry teachers but science and art teachers are also welcome to request a Pintstein substitute teacher. Few teachers have the time to learn a complicated and frustrating new technology. Let Pintstein make your life easier.

"Scratch your own itch"... I heard Massimo Banzi say this in a TED Talk (https://www.ted.com/talks/massimo_banzi_how_arduino_is_open_sourcing_imagination?) and it rang an accord with me, I paused playback and mulled it over for a minute.

There's something about Making a Thing that is spiritually soothing, and even more satisfying when you make the TOOL to make the thing..

Start to End, Cradle to Grave, Concept to Implementation.
Scratch your own Itch.
The possibilities are endless.

I am a small business owner. I am a one man company, it doesn't get any smaller than that!

I repair packaging machines in factories in So Cal. I go somewhere different every day. I love it. I repair shrink wrap machines, pallet wrappers, case sealers and erectors, fillers, lidders, tray sealers, conveyors, the list goes on and on. Highly specialized and highly in demand. Kind of like an industrial handy man. I understand electricity very well, mechanical very well, pneumatics well enough, and I really try to stay away from hydraulics.

Early on I acquired the nickname of MacGyver. I knew I could use a 3D printer for work, and it took me a while, and now I am printing out some industrial parts, like a disconnect operator, safety keys so I can run a machine with the doors open, patches to save a broken chain cover, a universal cabinet key, all kinds of stuff. I see more and more opportunity every day.
Just learning how to 3D print and looking for more ideas and different things to try!
